init_text:
How Worried Should We Be About Screen Time During the Pandemic?

The coronavirus pandemic ended the screen time debate: Screens won. We all now find ourselves on our screens for school, for work and for connecting with family and friends during this time of social distancing and increased isolation.

But should we be worried about this excessive screen use right now? Or should we finally get over it and embrace the benefits of our digital devices?

---

In my opinion,

actions.name: text-insert
actions.text: American adults need to worry less about screen time and more about letting children sit alone on screens all day.

actions.name: text-insert
actions.text: We need to let them enjoy the company of their friends online, talk to them about the huge amount of bullying and meanness in the virtual world too

actions.name: text-insert
actions.text: And we need to talk to them about staying safe in this virtual world.

actions.name: text-insert
actions.text: Just how much screen time is too much screen time?

actions.name: text-insert
actions.text: It's all a matter of balance.

actions.name: text-insert
actions.text: It's not just the amount of time that matters, but also what you're doing with your device.

actions.name: text-insert
actions.text: Spending too much time on screens might be a problem if you're using a device to escape from the things around you or if you are ignoring your family

actions.name: text-insert
actions.text: Screens can make you feel more isolated from your surrounding.

actions.name: text-insert
actions.text: And when you're depressed, spending more time on screen might even make things worse.

actions.name: text-insert
actions.text: Once you have a good balance of activities around screen time, it isn't bad.

actions.name: text-insert
actions.text: There is a lot of evidence that video games improve hand-eye coordination and sharpen the reaction time.
